The hemipenis is rather globular (though not as globular as that of 

B. minima

), short and broad, with a flattened apical end with a clear lip around its circumference (Fig. 
6
). The whole of the apex is somewhat tilted sulcally. A pair of structures emerge from the apical surface, each of which consists of three fleshy lobes, of which the middle lobe is the shortest. The truncus is smooth and lacks any trace of calyces.
